deck_excerpt: flood the field with powerful effect dragons
deck_description: its pendulum dragons pretty simple.
Spin your wheels, then profit

The gameplay is pretty standard at this point, so I'll just go over some highlights.

Tearlaments Kaleido-Heart is present here because her special summon gets past your extra deck lockouts, and consequently triggers her shuffle. No Tearlaments cards have been included in the main deck because they all fusion summon during the chain they're sent to the graveyard, when you'll probably be locked out. Mereologic Aggregator has not been released in the TCG yet, but I highly recommend including it once it is; it will be VERY powerful in this deck. Neo Blue-Eyes Ultimate Dragon and Eldlich the Mad Golden Lord are only here as ATK targets for Dogmatika Punishment. You don't need to keep duplicates of all those monsters in the extra deck, except for Elder Entity N'tss (keep that at 3 since its destruction is not once per turn), but I do recommend keeping at least one of each.

Since the main deck is good enough at taking out monsters, the side deck has been filled up to deal with spells/traps. But like any side deck, feel free to replace it with whatever works best for you.

If you decide to try this deck, please let me know how it plays in the comments.

deck_excerpt: An updated Version of my old Suship Deck with support of the "Xyz"-cards
deck_description: The Suship monsters don't need their Xyz-materials after their summon. So you can use their material for cards like Xyz-Gift and Xyz-Remora, which are great for extension into other Rank 4s. They are searchable via Generation Force. You can also use it to search Xyz Import and Xyz Veil. Xyz Import is great against Tearlament due to the way Xyz-Material works. And Xyz Veil is just for a bit of protection, which may come up

Honestly this was my favourite deck pre-list, so I spent the past week cooking up a new list

TL;DR
By sacrificing some consistency, the Nephtys engine gives the spright core access to slightly higher ceiling, and a much better grind game

Card by Card

Nephtys Engine
1 x Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys - Needed for setup line, also will steal a game every now and then
1 x Matriarch of Nephthys - Nessacry for some lines, as a summon off Devotee of Nephthys 
3 x Disciple of Nephthys  - Half a starter, not the best card, but needed for the deck to function
1 x Cerulean Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys - Mainly a search target, but useful for breaking boards when summoned with Conductor of Nephthys 
3 x Conductor of Nephthys  - Represents 3-5 monsters, helps break boards, makes you a sandwich
2 x Devotee of Nephthys - Easy to search, so you only need 2, is a one card Gigantic Spright when searched with Pre-Preparation of Rites 
2 x Rebirth of Nephthys - See above, also somtimes is removal
3 x Pre-Preparation of Rites - Our one card starter, lets the engine function

Spright
3 x Spright Blue - Searches Spright Jet 
3 x Spright Jet - Searches Spright Starter 
3 x Spright Starter - Summons Spright Blue 
1 x Spright Carrot - Is a name and a negate
1 x Spright Red - Is a name and a negate
1 x Spright Double Cross - Is just better Crackdown 
2 x Swap Frog - Makes Toadally Awesome 
1 x Cyber-Stein - I can explain

Staples
3 x Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring - Still worth maining, it's an FTK against every rouge deck
3 x Infinite Impermanence - By far the best handtrap in the format, steals Tear games
3 x Dark Ruler No More - If spright and tear are good, this card is

Extra
1 x The Last Warrior from Another Planet - :)
1x Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder - Best going second tool in the deck
1x Downerd Magician - Makes Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder better
1x Toadally Awesome - Part of your standered end board
1x Sky Cavalry Centaurea - Makes Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder and clears hard to out threats
2 x Gigantic Spright - Crystron Halqifibrax for level 2's
1 x Abominable Unchained Soul - Our summon off I:P Masquerena 
2 x Spright Elf - Why
1 x Spright Sprind - Lets us dump Cyber-Stein 
2 x Nephthys, the Sacred Preserver - Part of our setup line
1 x I:P Masquerena - Tags out for a pop
1 x Pitknight Earlie - Is a negate that triggers off either Spright Elf or I:P Masquerena 

Side
3 x Nibiru, the Primal Being - Anti combo
2 x D.D. Crow - Anti tear
3 x Cosmic Cyclone - Ok guys, but with all due respect. How are you not prepared for mine at this point. It’s a little ridiculous to not have a well thought out plan when entering a tournament.
3 x Mystic Mine - Ok guys, but with all due respect. How are you not prepared for mine at this point. It’s a little ridiculous to not have a well thought out plan when entering a tournament.
3 x Dimensional Barrier - FTK against Tear, and everyone who can't afford a Spright deck, so is still playing Despia/Swordsoul|
1 x Naturia Exterio - Swap with The Last Warrior from Another Planet in case of mine burn

deck_excerpt: Darklords 60 card Highlander Deck, made for the Monthly Novakin Master Duel Tournament. Abomination, do not attempt at home.
deck_description:
So this deck is mostly copied over from "Gahena: The Desecrated Garden" by Arsenicroute978, with some marked differences:

Removed cards:

Inferno Reckless Summon - Mostly because this doesn't make sense? This is a Highlander deck so why does it have a card that only summons cards with the same name as an already special summoned monster?

Magical Contract Door - Personally, I don't want to give any of the spells to the opponent, either because they'll become dud cards or because I'll need them myself (not to mention they might end up helping the opponent).

Vanity's Ruler - I dislike this card. About the only reason it's gone.

Darklord Descent - The chances of me having Darklords of the same level as an opponent's monster is a bit too low for my liking compared to what I've added.

Celestial Transformation - While I see its uses for Tribute summoning by adding monsters on the field, I feel like I have better options in that regard.

Added Cards:

Celestial Knightlord Parshath - The Sanctuary in the Sky and The Sanctum of Parshath both work well in this deck in general, and Celestial Lord only supports it further. The ability to change out cards with Fairy monsters in the deck, especially with the methods I have for moving cards from the graveyard, is fairly powerful, and so is the ability to immediately replace a fallen Fairy Monster.

The Sanctuary in the Sky - Mostly to activate the power of Celestial Knightlord, but still a useful card nonetheless.

The Sanctum of Parshath - More directly useful than Sanctuary in the Sky, but also takes up a spot on the Spell/Trap zone instead of the Field Spell zone. Good for returning Fairies in the deck and getting back the one protective Counter Trap of the deck, especially since you put them all on the top of the deck.

Forbidden Droplet - Gotta have a staple in there somewhere, and it is part of the theme and archetype.

Grapha, Dragon Lord of Dark World - Exceptionally good card with the mechanics of the deck - destroys opponent's cards when discarded from the hand, and denies resources for the opponent if destroyed by the opponent. Sure I won't be able to special summon it by its effect, but even Tribute summoning it wouldn't be too hard + it would support the effects of Darkest Diabolos.

Darkest Diabolos, Lord of the Lair - Amazing Anti-Kaiju counter, easy to summon (at least in this deck), and capable of draining resources from the opponent.

I feel good about this deck, personally, which means I'll hard-brick and lose immediately. RNJesus help me...

deck_excerpt: An 'Exodia Smoke' Deck for Yugi/Kaiba format (May 2002). Obliterate!!!
deck_description:
An 'Exodia Smoke' Deck for Yugi/Kaiba format (May 2002). Obliterate!!!

Exodia Smoke: This deck only works if your opponent doesn't know what you are doing. It's a very complicated deck to run. Be smart Game 2, don't use your Last Wills too early, wait until you have drawn 2 Exodia pieces already, protect your Hane-Hanes so you can bounce an Exodia piece back to your hand, use Card Destruction when you have 1 piece and bring it back with Monster Reborn. 

 

The initial deck tries its hardest to look like a normal deck, but every card choice is important.

EXAMPLE 1: The best draw spell is Card Destruction. You need to use it to draw to Exodia faster, but what if you have some pieces in your hand already? Simple: Summon the Exodia Piece then activate Card Destruction, then return the Exodia piece to your hand with either Hane-Hane or by attacking your opponent's Wall of Illusion. However many people don't run Wall of Illusion in their main deck anymore because they fear it being exploited by Man-Eater Bug therefore, to make sure they side in Wall of Illusion for Game 2 DON'T MAIN MAN-EATER BUG.

EXAMPLE 2: You definitely need your Swords of Revealing Light for Game 2 so to ensure that your opponent doesn't keep/put thier De-Spell in for Game 2 DON'T MAIN SWORDS OF REVEALING LIGHT.

EXAMPLE 3: After seeing Exodia Game 2 your opponent will hopefully side in Card Destruction, and if you managed to activate yours 3-4 times in the first 2 duels they will be very scared of losing the monsters in their hand now that you're both running it, so they will over commit and you will activate your newly sided in JUST DESSERTS for Game 3.

deck_excerpt: How is this archetype so old and still so unplayable?
deck_description: Despite the huge number of members the archetype has Ninja Grandmaster Hanzo is still the only playable Ninja monster as it searches for Ninjitsu Art of Super-Transformation which then sends a monster your opponent controls to summon: 1) a floodgate in Amorphage Goliath 2) a quick effect pop in Dinowrestler Pankratops or 3) Fallen of Albaz to get rid of another one of your opponent's monster to fusion summon (Always remember to keep a card in hand to discard off of the effect of Albaz if you plan to do this play). Thankfully, Ninjas have received a makeover in Darkwing Blast, these new cards will take some time to get to Master Duel tho. Also, despite the ammount of traps this deck plays, we can still go second thanks to tools like Pankratops, Fallen of Albaz, Super Polymerization and Evenly Matched.
Every card is purposeful and the art is phenomenal.

deck_excerpt: Now updated for the 03/10/2022 Limited and Forbidden List!
deck_description:
A deck that combines both the "Labrynth" and "Amazement" themes!

The Extra Deck is there to be used as fuel for Pot of Extravagance. However, I built it in such a way that it can effectively be used should you decide to play around with "Dogmatika Punishment". I'm a bit torn between "Amaze Attraction Thrill Train" and "Amaze Attraction Viking Vortex". They both have their positives and one can be substituted for the other in accordance to your sensibilities. 

The Side Deck is tailored to combat common threats at my Local OTS. Solemn Judgment and Anti-Spell Fragrance put the kibosh on mass S/T removal cards such as Harpie's Feather Duster and Lightning Storm while Different Dimension Ground can be reset by Lovely Labrynth every turn to put the brakes on decks like Tearlament. Dimensional Barrier is just a great counter all-around and Evenly Matched is for breaking apart large boards when made to go second.

You're free to alter the Side Deck to suit whatever needs make the most sense for you.
A Fusion Deck that’s basically pay-to-win with a Guardian Chimera and many consistent options to summon from extra with powerful fusions for the cost.

deck_excerpt: No more halq? Fine, will still find way to play Libromancers (Oct 2022 banlist).
deck_description:
Absolute heat. Never bricks, except when it does. Actually pend w/o scales.

God board is elf, baronne, libromancer doombroker + trap, gryphon rider + token (+ fateful), ecclesia + fleurdelis (in hand), shaddoll schism, dogmatika punishment, and 3+ cards in hand for follow-up.

Nadir gets you into dogmatika and/or shaddoll engine -> ritual for libromancer engine (need e-tele, geek boy, field spell, or fire for libro combo after that) -> diviner engine (baronne + elf). If you have a way into the adventure engine, make sure you don't activate diviner's effect on normal summon instead normal -> elf -> reborn diviner -> effect on ss -> baronne w/ fire.

Can also scythe lock easily (only for people who actually want to win -- or glue-eaters). Just get scythe off benten.

Eradicator is trouble (thanks for banning reboot konami)... so either scoop, side-in night beam, or side-in lava golem to eat their tribute (last two options obviously only work if they don't activate in standby).

Vanity and banisher are decent options, but they definitely restrict your end boards, so its a trade-off.
Primary to go first, but don't worry if you go second. If you go first set up negations with UTC for the kill.

Fun Deck using the Poker Knights as an engine with Utopia support to help get into the big guys. Always looking for ways to improve the deck.

deck_name: HERO Deck List Post October 2022 Banlist
deck_description:
Fusion Destiny is back at 3!!!

What is the best meta killing side deck cards?

  • Dimension Shifter: Kills all meta including Tearamants, Spright, and Swordsoul. Great for going second when you can't establish Masked HERO Dark Law before your opponent can make their first move.
  • Dimensional Barrier: Stops Tearamants and Swordsoul as well as Spright to a lesser extent. Also perfect aganist the best antimeta decks like Phantom Knights, Drytron, Pendulum Magician and the mirror match. Be careful when using this aganist Tearamants because it also will negate your own Fusion Monster's effects if you declared Fusion Monsters. It's best to be used with Destiny HERO - Plasma and Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer when the monster is already in the graveyard and ready to come back the next turn prior to activiting this card.
  • Twin Twister: Mystic Mine can go die and rot in deepest pits of hell. What was Konami thinking by not banning this card?!

deck_excerpt: Make Masked Beserker Cydrafinity from Magical Scientist!
deck_description:
Get Magical Scientist ASAP with draw cards. First turn, get Cydra Infinity out. If you have Brilliant and/or Mathematician, go for Tenyi Berserker or Unicorn. If you have MCII, go for Dark Law using MagSci. PotB allows you to still play Brilliant if you topdeck Garnet after discarding Garnet via MCII or 141's effects.

LotD: Link Evolution has a crashing problem so the limitations are within a handful number of summons to create a winning board. Only 6 summons for a Cydrafinity + Dark Law which stops 95% of Singleplayer foe decks. 

Can Side TornadoD + 2 x any 4-star Fusions to pop opposing Field Spells or S/T to create a stronger field T1, though making a second Cydrafinity on your T2 makes you somewhat vulnerable with only 2000 LP.  

This Deck is made for play in the Singleplayer mode of the Nintendo Switch game YuGiOh Legacy of the Duelist: Link Evolution.

deck_excerpt: A pure DM deck aiming to be as competitive as possible in the current meta.
deck_description:
TL;DR:
Make Dragoon with Timaeus on turn 1 if you don't have Eternal Soul & Dark Magical Circle set. If you do, make Dragon Knight instead.

Table of Contents

  •  
  • Card Choice Explanations
  • Main Deck
    • Monsters
    • Spells
    • Traps
  • Extra Deck
    • Fusion Monsters
    • Super Poly Targets
    • Link Monsters
  • Side Deck

Card Choice Explanations

We run 40 cards and no more to have maximum consistency, due to some card interactions like Prep and Salvation, we "technically" run less than 40.

Main Deck

Monsters

2x Dark Magician: 3 is too bricky, you want them on the board or in the GY but usually not in your hand.

2x Timaeus: Can also run just 1, but 2 is nice since you can fuse into either Dragoon or Dragon Knight, but usually want both at some point in the match. Searchable with Illusion of Chaos. You can use Magician's Salvation as tribute to summon Timaeus after using it's effect to set Eternal Soul. Getting him in your opening hand is not the worst thing, if you can get a DM onto the board or at least into your hand, provided that you have something suitable as tribute to special him to the board.

1x Palladium Oracle Mahad: Allows you to draw more with Soul Servant, nice if you pitch it with Illusion of Chaos or Soul Servant and draw it on the following turn or of Soul Servant's effect.

1x Dark Magician Girl: More draws with Soul Servant, can be dumped to the GY by Magician's Souls. You never want to draw her, but she can be special'd from the hand or deck by The Dark Magicians effect.

3x Magician's Rod: Search any DM spell with this, tribute it for Timaeus or link it off to the GY with Artemis to bounce it back on the opponent's turn.

3x Magician's Souls: Can dump DM, DMG, Mahad and Illusion, to either summon itself and get rid of up to 2 spells (like Magician's Salvation after setting Eternal Soul) from either the field or hand and draw up to 2 new cards. If you already have Eternal Soul set you ideally want to use this to draw and not to special a DM to the field, unless you really need the DM on the field in that turn to fusion into Dragoon or Dragon Knight.

2x Illusion of Chaos: The reason why this deck actually works. Can search you any monster you need to advance your combos and pitch a brick back to the deck. You really want to put your best efforts into getting this into your hand on turn 1. If there is no more deck shuffling to do, you can also put the card itself back on the deck to draw it on the following turn or with Soul Servant. It's on board effect is also useful to negate and bounce itself back, but I actually never had myself summon this to the board with Secrets of Dark Magic at all. If neccessary, you can fetch Mahad with this, pitch it and draw it with either SS, Magician's Souls or just on the following turn.

3x Ash Blossom: We want to play the best handtrap in the game.

Spells

2x Dark Magicial Circle: You could run 3, but 2 is just fine. You can use both of its effects in one turn. Use it to get a card you need off of your deck and banish whatever your opponent has on the field after summoning a DM. Works like a charm with Eternal Soul and can be protected by Dragon Knight.

1x Magician's Salvation: Essentially makes your deck a 39 card deck, sets Eternal Soul, can be fetched by Terraforming. Can be used to special Timaeus or used by Magician's Souls for draw. The secondary effect of specialing a DMG after a DM has been summoned and vice versa is also handy.

2x Secret Village of the Spellcasters: Does your opponent rely on spells? Then play this card, if not, side it out for something more useful.

1x Dark Magic Attack: Same as above, basically a searchable Feather Duster in this deck.

3x Preparation of Rites: Basically means you run 5 copies of Illusion of Chaos and now a 36 card deck. Do you have Illusion of Chaos already in hand? Dump this with Magician's Souls and draw something new.

1x Terraforming: After Magician's Salvation and Preparation of Rites, this means you now run a 35 card deck. Obviously even better if you have Secret Village in your main deck. Possibly better to replace it with Crossout or Called by if you don't.

2x Secrets of Dark Magic: Quick-Play fusion, use it during the battle phase or on your opponent's turn. The Ritual Summoning effect is rather niche.

3x Soul Servant: What could be better than running a 35-36 card deck? Exactly, additionally having the ability to draw up to 3 cards with one of them being either a recycled one or the exact one you need. This card has a ton of different use cases and is like a swiss-army knife. The main reason why we play 2 bricks in Mahad and DMG. Get either of them on the GY and this card is already a +1. The main thing you want to search with Rod unless you have no way to fusion or no suitable monster on the field or in the GY to draw and even then you can still use it to put something useful (back) on your deck to draw it with any other effect.

3x Super Poly: Break any board with Garura, Mudragon, Dragostapelia or Starving Venom. Can dump a brick to the GY to make it useful again. Rarely use it to fusion a DM monster, it's usually bet to set it and use it on the opponent's turn or using it to push for lethal during the battle phase.

Traps

2x Eternal Soul: Never run this at 3, you can search it with so many effects and usually do not want it in your opening hand as you want other stuff to get a DM into the GY (or on the field) first. Running Salvation helps a lot and you can get it back off the GY if you really need with Soul Servant. Not much to do if it gets banished though.

3x Infinite Impermanence: For going second and disrupting the opponent. Also handy to screw with the backrow. Can be replaced with any other handtrap or Dark Ruler No More.

Extra Deck

Fusion Monsters

1x Dark Magician the Dragon Knight: Protects Eternal Soul and possibly Dark Magicial Circle, you want to fusion into this instead of Dragoon if you have both set already as this combination is insanely hard to deal with. Especially since even if your Dragon Knight is somehow sent to the GY you can just summon it back with Eternal Soul. Having this AND Dragoon out at the same time is possibly a game winning play.

1x Red Eyes Dark Dragoon: The reason this deck is functioning. A very annoying and hard to deal with boss monster which you ideally want to have out on your first turn. The omni negate buff just adds insult to injury. As he is a spellcaster, he can be revived by Selene and interacts nicely with other cards like Master of Chaos, Secret Village of the Spellcasters or Rivalry.

1x The Dark Magicians: Allows you to draw, brings out DMG and DM after being dealt with, very easy to fuse into and a very iconic card.

1x Master of Chaos: Use DM and Illusion to get Mahad and DM, DMG or Illusion of Chaos (+ to bounce it back to hand with its own effect) special'd from the GY. Then you can tribute your just summoned monsters to banish your opponent's monsters. You can possibly retrieve the card you used to fusion summon Master or any other useful spell you need from your GY once Master is destroyed.

Super Poly Targets

Garura & Mudragon: The two current baseline monsters to break board with Super Poly. Same Attribute and Type? => Garura. Same Attribute but different Type? => Mudragon.

Starving Venom, Dragostapelia & Triphyoverutum: Just fuse into whatever you need or tech in something else depending on your local meta. Triphy is kinda only for matchups where the opponent is also mostly playing Darkness Monsters.

Link Monsters

1x Imduk the World Chalice Dragon: Link DM off to the GY, use it to fuse into Dragoon or crash into an opponent's monster.

1x Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden: Used to bounce Rod, link it off, and tribute Artemis on the opponent's turn.

1x I:P Masquerena: We play Link monsters, so we play this card. Link Rod and Magician's Souls, have Eternal Soul set, special DM on the opponent's turn and link into Knightmare Unicorn or Selene for either removal or specialing a spellcaster back from the GY.

1x Knightmare Unicorn: See above

1x Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy: Use it to special an opponent's dark monster out of his GY and get Rod or Souls out of your deck into your hand once he is destroyed.

1x Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians: Use it to special any spellcaster (likely the one you used + I:P to link into this) from the GY (remember even Dragoon is a spellcaster). Reaching enough counters is not an issue as we play a ton of spells and it also counts the opponent's spells.

1x Accesscode Talker: A pricey Link-4 that you can link into with Selene and her summon, as he only requires 2+ effect monsters, so you usually don't want DM back from Selene. Use it to destroy any of your opponent's cards for just banishing one of your Link Monsters from the GY and you can even use this effect multiple times if you use a monster with a different Attribute to banish.

Side Deck

Side deck can be made 3-ofs depending on what local meta you are facing, these are just suggestions.

I personally run 3x Crow, 3x Cosmic Cyclone, 3x Rivalry, 3x Solemn Strike, 1x Crossout, 1x Anima, 1x Triphyoverutum.

You usally take out Secret Village of the Spellcasters + Terraforming or Dark Magic Attack for the side tech as these do nothing against decks that don't rely on spells / backrow. Even additionally replacing Ash with Crow vs decks that do a lot of graveyard shenanigans is also a valid choice.

Skill Drain is more of an emergency tech, I've seen it used but I'd always prefer Dark Ruler no More, as your Eternal Soul does only protect your DMs against opponent's effects, but not your own.

And no, we don't play Mystic Mine.

Noteable Combos

Climb the Link-Ladder with Rod + Souls into I:P-Masq, use Eternal Soul on your opponent's turn to get into Selene or Knightmare Unicorn.

deck_name: Phantom Knights but its a Fusion Deck
deck_description: If you know how the standard Pure Phantom Knights work then you should be able to figure out how this deck deviates from that. Fusions! Thanks to Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio and Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra, we can access any fusion card we could possibly want from deck! That means we can search our Fusion Destiny, Instant Fusion, Ready Fusion, and even Super Polymerization! Since Scorpio gets 2 level 3 monsters, we can make Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss and continue the combo! Instant and Ready Fusion are here as extenders, using either Flame Ghost or Zombie Warrior. You can also use either of those fusion cards for Sea Monster of Theseus, and use a spare level 3 on board to make Borreload Savage Dragon!
Runick Spright

Suship is able to draw multiple cards over the course of a turn while making their boss monsters.

The problem here is none of the archetpye XYZ have meaningful disruption. While a lot of decklists just focus on drawing more extenders to spam the board with XYZs that essentially don't stop your opponent from running you over this one opts to draw into handtraps/traps instead to disrupt your opponent on their turn. Since this deck can consistently outpout their 3 XYZ monsters on the first turn (sometimes even without the normal summon) playing more extenders is simply overkill and will deplete you all of your resources while still leaving you vulnerable to succumb to your opponents wrath

Essentially all of the handtraps/traps can be exchanged with other traps/handtraps and the deck would still function exactly the same as long as those cards replacing it fulfill the same role: protecting your board/disrupting your opponent. This last statement is relevant for budget players looking to build the deck irl, cards like Forbidden Chalice still do a great job if you can't afford the Ash's as an example, same goes for the Zeus, Exciton Knight is already a strong equalizer. The Side-Deck is also completely replacable with other blow-out cards like Raigeki and such.
Brujitas!!!!!

Simple n Cheap

A cheap version of Branded Dragonmaid. The main goal is to go into Masquerade the Blazing Dragon or Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon and Dragonmaid Sheou  on the same field to give you protection, burn combo decks, and a free omninegate. Sheou also allows you to recycle your dragonmaids, along with Lubellion the Searing Dragon  allowing you to recycle everything else that can be used for fusion summoning (as well as being a big dragon to use to get sheou out).
It can struggle against heavy-negate filled boards, and Super Polymerization kills it, but that's the same issue that Branded Despia has, and super poly kills most decks right now regardless. 
Tri-Brigade Mercourier is here as the main hand trap, as this is based off my IRL deck and I don't have 3 copies of Ash/Belle, and, if you use it as fusion material for Lubelion (either using Branded in White  or Albion the Branded Dragon) it allows you to search a copy of either Fallen of Albaz, Albion the Shrouded Dragon, or, preferably Aluber the Jester of Despia, allowing you to grab a branded spell/trap. 

Ghost Reaper & Winter Cherries is my main side-deck card to go against other Branded/Fusion engines, as I usually use it to target Lubelion (so they can't recycle cards from GY or Banish). When I get some copies of Crossout Designator, I plan on siding that to deal with Super Poly, Ash, or Branded Fusion. If you decide not to go into Mirrorjade, Artifact Lancea is a good option to prevent your field from getting banished, or help prevent Swordsoul from popping off.

deck_description:
A 'Backrow Control' Deck for Yugi/Kaiba format (May 2002). Take back control of the duel.

This Is my take on Backrow Control. The Deck is not very good. But it's not meant to be used like this. The idea is actually to side into Backrow Control for game 2 or 3. Activate Card Destruction as often as you can so that your opponent fears it. Then in the next game, they will set their power spells in fear of loosing them. That's when you get the upper hand with this deck.

One of my favorite cards (Kuriboh) and his homies rig the stage for you to play in their fun minigames. Prepare to toss coins and roll some dice for and with these little idiots. 

Have fun and I hope you enjoy,

-Yules

deck_name: Adamancipator Spright But Illegal because of the banlist
deck_description:
This deck is dead now so im just copying what i said in the description and comments. I wish i released this list sooner for people to use before it got banned but im going to explain why this deck was so powerful.

This deck grinds so ridiculously well, plays through disruptions, and puts up big negates boards. Its so versatile. Even if this deck gets drnm'd the opponents still has to spend resources on building a board that break yours entire board and you make them think about which cards to destroy (Spright Elf, Toadally Awesome, Guardian, and Savage) Deck is crazy good. Tier 1 minimum but borderline Tier 0 Dupe Frog protects apollousa from being attacked during the bp (Giving you more freedom to use her negates), Being able to set spright starter for one extra negate (Can be used after being drnm'd) Toadally Awesome grabbing Cartorhyn for double normal to increase the decks grind ability Being able to re-use (prevent from being banished) cartorhyn and plaguspreader cuz they can be used to xyz summon Gigantic Spright, and Spright Elf just existing.

For more context the ronintoadin and halq ban hurt this list the most. Halq i dont need to explain why but ronintoadin wasn't only an amazing pathway to Toadally Awesome. The follow up play during turn 3 it gave allowed you to easily make Spright Elf for further extension or Accesscode talker. Ronintoadin turn 3 with 2 frogs in gy was incredibly powerful. Also not having Toadally Awesome means not being able to grab Cartorhyn from gy for even further Turn 3 follow up. Essentially this decks ability to build a HUGE board with amazing grind is gone

I am leaving this list here for those who just want to have fun with it or in case Halq or Ronintoadin become unbanned in the future. Do what you will with this deck list.

EDIT: Here also a download link to all my EDOPro combo and duel replays using the deck https://www.mediafire.com/file/6mmjo2himhrb0g6/EDOPro_Spright_Adam_Combo_Replays.rar/file

This is a deck in response to the banlist that dropped yesterday. Paleofrogs is one of my favorite decks and Ronintoadin getting banned kills the frog engine completely. This deck is pretty much a Dinorabbit version of Paleofrogs based off of how I used to play Paleofrogs and how Dzeeff used Rescue Rabbit in his Paleofrog list he made in a year ago. 

The main deck is the usual Paleofrog deck I play just with 3 Rescue Rabbit and a 3rd Unexpected Dai and it is on Lord of the Heavenly Prison. I did change the extra a bit, but dont think that it is correct yet as the frog engine being gone changes so much, so I will be changing it again at some point. Marincess Coral Anemone and Accesscode Talker for example might not be fit for this deck anymore as it will be much harder to create the materials now. 

Any help or feedback is welcome, as I want to work towards finding the new way to play "Paleofrogs". 

o7 to both Frog the Jam and Ronintoadin.

deck_excerpt: I'm actually really bad at math irl
deck_description:
Haven't played TCG in months but came back for a small 8-man locals with Mathmech!

A very standard build, I wanted to cut down enough cards to hit the golden 40-card count while also keeping enough for consistency.

I'm also running only one Mathmech Superfactorial (and such only playing one Primathmech Alembertian ) so I can also play the one Mathmech Induction along with Mathmech Equation.

 

For my match-ups I went against Madolche, Tri-Brigade Spright, and Marincess.

For Madolche I went second game 1, I was able to Infinite Impermanence one of the XYZ monsters, and used D.D. Crow on an attempt to shuffle a monster in the grave while Madolche Salon was up.

I didn't side for game 2.

For game 2, I went first and set up the standard Cyberse Wicckid , I:P Masquerena , and Linguriboh board with a Mathmech Superfactorial set. On opponent's turn, I made Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess and then made a Primathmech Alembertian . Final turn was an Accesscode Talker for game.

 

For Tri-Brigade Spright I went first game 1 and set up the standard board (mentioned above). Then made Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess and Primathmech Alembertian with a negate from Mathmech Diameter . I luckily sniped a Triple Tactics Talent from the hand and had enough negates to stop plays.

I sided my Cosmic Cyclones and Harpie's Feather Duster because I wanted a chance to force out the Tri-Brigade Revolt since I was going second.

Game 2 I went second and faced a board with Spright Red , Spright Elf , Ancient Warriors Oath - Double Dragon Lords , and Pitknight Earlie .I  opened Duster and my opp revolted early into Tri-Brigade Rugal the Silver Sheller , Opponent DDLed a lil early, and was able to go into a double attacking Accesscode Talker hitting for exact lethal over the Rugal and Pitknight Earlie since 1200 lp was taken for Spright Red .

 

For Marincess, I went second game 1. Opened with Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and Effect Veiler so my opponent could only go into the Link-3 marincess with the Marincess Wave in hand. I was able to close it with Accesscode Talker double attacking again.

I sided the same as for my Tri-Spright game.

I went second for game 2, went full combo into Accesscode Talker. I had a Called by the Grave for my opponent's Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion that was used on my Mathmech Sigma.

deck_excerpt: The Tindangler returns, despite the banning of Chaos Ruler.
deck_description:
First of all, I'd like to give credit to Halfmiss, for both providing the original deck this was based on, and suggesting the changes made to it.

I've always enjoyed both the maths-inspired aesthetics and the underdog nature of Tindangle as a deck, ever since it first appeared in Yu-Gi-Oh! VRAINS. With the release of Tindangle Jhrelth, the deck came together in a way that was surprisingly potent, though very much still casual. Before the most recent banlist as of writing, I used a Rokket package to make Chaos Ruler, the Chaotic Magical Dragon, to dig for Tindangles and send many useful cards to the Graveyard, such as Tindangle Delaunay and Tindangle Intruder. However, on the most recent banlist, Chaos Ruler has been Forbidden, so we're in search of a new supplement engine to support our underpowered and slow-to-start deck.

With the recent release of Krawler Soma, we can find our answer in FLIP synergies. By reducing its own Level to 2 and summoning two more Level 2 Krawlers, we have more than enough material to summon Ghostrick Socuteboss and utilise that engine to make Number F0: Utopic Draco Future. Furthermore, the search from the second copy of Ghostrick Angel of Mischief can be Ghostrick Scare, to flip up the spare Krawler, Soma's target from summoning, and any spare Tindangles we have sitting face-down.

The appeal of the Tindangle deck itself comes from Tindangle Delaunay. Its effect in the graveyard, combined with Intruder, means that you can very abruptly put up a wall of 3-4 FLIP monsters with sticky effects. It takes some set up to get going, and without a supplementary engine the first turn is anything but explosive, but if you manage to survive a few turns, the deck's grind game is unparalleled.

The selection of staples, and the layout in the Side Deck, are very rough. I don't currently play in the Yu-Gi-Oh! metagame, so I don't know what the best options are. These are mostly just holdovers from suggestions from others for old versions of the deck. If you want to play this deck more casually and remove things like hand traps and floodgates, I can suggest filling the space with Nagel's Protection, a Tindangle support card that benefits from being sent to the graveyard by Jhrelth, and Junk Sleep, a FLIP support card that lets you constantly re-use their effects. Also, Gergonne's End will rarely come up, but it's very funny when it does, and it enables the Link Material effect of Tindangle Trinity. Other options in the Extra Deck include Shaddoll Construct, for what is arguably the FLIP deck most often face-up, and it can Fusion Summon El Shaddoll Winda without any Main Deck investment.

deck_excerpt: Big money big boss monster big synchros
deck_description:
Why Raviel and Fabled?

 

I just wanted to use them together. Demon angels cool

 

Does it work?

 

To a degree, yes. Fabled lacks a powerful boss monster, which Raviel (kinda) provides. Each archtype has several cards that have discard related effects, and so they can be used in tandem with each other to prepare for specific setups. Outside of discarding and graveyard related effects, you're essentially playing two different games at once. Fabled is going to shoot for synchros while your Sacred Beast monsters are going to try to bring Raviel out.  Depending on the hand you may only go for one first, and then potentially draw into the next one later. Fallen Paradise combined with Fabled Ragin means that your always going to be able to draw two more cards regardless of where you start. Shooting for negates is really what Fabled is going to be aiming for here. Herald, F.A. Dragster, and maybe even Baronne are your eventual targets. Herald in particular can be easy seeing how you'll often have a leftover level 2 monster in Dark Beckoning Beast. 

 

What About That Extra Deck?

 

Herald and F.A. for easy negates, linkuriboh for the occasional leftover level 1 monster, Brionac for non-destruction card removal (and discards), Chaos Ruler, and Baronne for some more boss monsters. Fabled Andwraith can force your opponent to dump a monster (if they don't read or if they only have monsters left in their hand), at worst acting as fodder for Raviel to get an attack boost, as best causing a discard on your way to a level 8 synchro. T.G. Hyper Liberian is there on the possiblity that you could get off tons of synchros, but it's honestly rarely feasible. I put cupid pitch at 2 precicely cuz it can be so hard to get to the higher level synchros, especially when you haven't yet gotten a huge card advantage. Levithan is just there to collect space tbh. Cool looking card, that's pretty much it.

 

What about that side deck?

 

Not a serious side deck, but some extra cards that seemed fun in theory but didn't make the cut due to consistency issues.

 

Anything else I should know?

The numbers on some cards isn't totally set in stone yet. I'm not super excited to have Raviel at 3 (two copies in a starting hand is a nightmare) but having him in your initial hand can save you a lot of headaches. Ash was originally at 3 but it can cause some issues when your trying to deplete your hand for Fabled Ragin. You can't really run any hand traps at all in this deck because of that.
The main deck that I've been playing at locals.

deck_name: Branded Tear post Oct. 2022 Banlist w/side
deck_excerpt: Branded Tear post list, utilizing a few non-standard ratios.
deck_description:
Not much changed for this deck (or really Tear at all) post list, but I still felt like posting.

Eccelsia is my sub for Snow, though I will be replacing with Red Cartesia once we get it.

My non-standard ratios are 2 Sulliek and 3 Merli.

I like Sulliek at 2 as I can comfortably mill one for a search and still have one to grab off Kit. You could play 3, but you really dont want to be drawing it. You could also play at 1, which is the more common choice, but I found that I was always wanting both the search and the negate. Its not awful to draw as pitching for Opening or Reino still nets a search, but I'd rather just search with Kit.

Merli at 3. I play as many fusion names as possible, simple as. I want to be seeing as many of my fusion monsters as I can, so I max on names.

My only non-standard choice is Dramaturge. I have tested with both it and Libitum and I found that having an additional body with a negate was much better, but honestly its personal prefrence.

Side deck is fairly standard, just replaced the Reboot with a thrid Cosmic. EEV is going to be insane going into this format.

This is definetly not the best way to play Tear, you lose to D-Barrier pretty hard and the Danger variant is much more explosive, but this deck has a few tricks up its sleeve. Its very consistent and makes use of Guardian Chimera very effectively as well as being able to set up for next turn during you opponents turn (searching for another Branded Fusion, mills of Kitkalos and Kaleido, resets with Tragedy). Its also cheaper than the Danger variant and stronger than the pure variant.

deck_excerpt: Summon multiple gigantic draconic boss monsters, methodically decimate your opponent’s board, then swing for game!
deck_description:
When Masterduel came out, one of the first decks I've built was Thunder Dragons. I arrived in competitive TCG when Colossus was just banned, and I wanted to see it's power for myself in a format where this "Mistake on legs" was legal. And boy, did it deliver! 
 
With Danger! cards and a Chaos support engine to help Thunder Dragons further their plays, Thunder Dragons hits hard, fast and while shrugging off interruption - easily OTKing an opponent from full lifepoints even though they have a complete board. Going first, an 3-4 negate Apollousa, a search-floodgate with Colossus, multiple pops with Titan, and a spell negate with Hope Harbinger is a nigh-unbreakable board!
 
With Chaos Thunder Dragon, you summon multiple gigantic draconic boss monsters, methodically decimate your opponent’s board, maintain resource advantage and when the time is right - swing for game!
 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
ARCHETYPES AND RATIOS
 
Forming the core, the THUNDER DRAGON cards in the maindeck consist of 16 cards. 3 Thunder Dragons, 3 Dragondark, 2 Dragonmatrix, 2 Dragonroar, 1 Dragonhawk, 2 Aloof Lupine, 2 Thunder Dragon Fusion and 1 Gold Sarcophagus. In the Extra Deck there are 2  Titan and 1 Colossus.
 
Enabling extension, searching, effect activation and milling of the Thunder Dragon cards, the CHAOS cards in the maindeck consist of 14 cards. 3 Chaos Space, 1 Black Dragon Collapserpent, 1 White Dragon Wyvernburster, 1 Chaos Valkyria and 1 Chaos Creator. The Assault Mode Engine is included as well to synchro summon Chaos Ruler - 2 Emergency Teleport, 1 One for One, 2 Psi-Reflector, 1 Assault Beast and 1 Assault Mode Activate. 
 
Simultaneously drawing cards and providing bodies on board, the DANGER! cards consist of 13 cards. 3 Bigfoot, 3 Thunderbird, 3 Nessie, 2 Tsuchinoko, and 2 Jackalope. 
 
The STAPLE cards in this deck take up 17 cards in this deck assisting with draw power, insulating plays and breaking the opponent's board. 3 Allure of Darkness and 1 Pot of Desires serve as draw power. 1 Impermanence, 1 Ash Blossom and 3 Maxx "C" along with 1 Crossout Designator and 2 Called By the Grave are for protection. 1 Dark Ruler No More and 1 Harpie's Feather Duster help break an opponent's board. 1 Monster Reborn, 1 Foolish Burial with it's target, 1 Gizmek Orochi serve as extension. 
 
This deck has 60 cards since almost every card is a starter, key cards are highly searcheable and a big deck decreases the chances of hard-drawing this deck's 2 bricks (Assault Beast and Assault Mode Activate). 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN

The GAMEPLAN with this deck is simple – lockdown the board going first, and OTK going second. 
 
 If the duel is forced into a grind-game, the Thunder Dragon resource loop and the previous turn's graveyard set-up can whittle an opponent down. Thunder Dragon Fusion can also be banished the turn after you use it to allow you to search for Thunder Dragonroar, which can be discarded to recover Thunder Dragon Fusion from the banished pile. Provided your GY/Banished Pile set-up, another Titan can be easily made. 
 
GOING FIRST, boards that end on Thunder Dragon Titan, Apollousa, Colossus and Hope Harbinger is often enough to ensure your survival until the next turn and keep your opponent at a stand still. The board might be even so far advanced that the opponent may straight up surrender, since the boards that deck deploys turn one are almost an FTK with the sheer number of negates, floodgates and interruption present. 
 
GOING SECOND, boards are easily picked apart by Thunder Dragon Titan and Accesscode's multiple pops. After breaking an opponent’s board, this deck can combo endlessly and easily generate enough gigantic monsters onboard to obliterate your opponent’s lifepoints in one turn.
 
COMBOS/GUIDELINES
 
Chaos Thunderdragon's combos are highly variable and hand dependent. Also, due to the chance-based nature of the Danger! cards and the other various draw cards (Pot of Desires, Allure of Darkness, Chaos Space), end-boards and available plays always change depending on what's in your hand. 
 
As you advance your plays, the hand, GY, banished pile and board tend to get very "snow-bally" accumulating more and more resources as you summon many times, draw multiple cards, build follow-up for future turns. 
 
 
 
There are no clear-cut combos for this deck, but here are some guidelines based on what cards you have available on your hand: 
 
  • Chaos Dragons = Cross Sheep: If you draw into Wyverburster or Collapserpent, these cards can make Cross-Sheep without normal summon. Summon one Chaos Dragon -> summon Striker Dragon -> Search the other Chaos Dragon -> Banish the Chaos Dragon in the GY to Special Summon -> If you used Chaos Space to search these dragons, banish Chaos Space for 1 draw -> Summon Cross-Sheep or another link monster of choice!
  • Cross-Sheep + Titan/Colossus: Fusion or special summon a Titan/Colossus to a zone Cross-Sheep points to summon another card from the GY. Depending on your situation, make Apollousa with multiple negates or Accesscode with 2+ pops!
  • Aloof Lupine + Thunder Dragon = Cross Sheep -> Apollousa/Titan: Normal summon Aloof Lupine -> Banish Thunder Dragon in hand and Thunder Dragonroar in deck -> Dragonroar eff to summon Thunder Dragondark from deck -> Link off Lupine + Dragondark for Cross-Sheep -> Dragondark eff to search Thunder Dragon Fusion -> Thunder Dragon Fusion eff to summon Titan to a zone Cross-Sheep points to -> Cross-Sheep effect to summon from GY Aloof Lupine -> Link off Cross-Sheep + Aloof Lupine + 1+ more monster(s) for 3-4 negate Apollousa. 
  • Dangers! cards: If you have lots of Danger! monsters in your hand, think about the chance of summoning them with the likelihood of discarding particular cards in your hand. If there is a valuable spell card you do not want to discard in your hand (like Monster Reborn or Thunder Dragon Fusion) be sure to set it first. Also, the OG Thunder Dragon can stock up your hand with 2 more cards so that the Danger! cards have more chance to successfully resolve and summon themselves with the +1 draw.
  • Draw cards and thinning out your deck: If you have a card/play that draws or digs in your deck, be sure to search as much as possible first. Search with Chaos Space, Thunder Dragons, Emergency Teleports first before summoning Chaos Ruler or using Pot of Desires! 
  • 2 Level 8s = Hope Harbinger/4 Material Zeus: If you have easy access to two level 8s, you can access to Rank 8 toolbox this deck offers. Going first, Hope Harbinger can be summoned with Numeron Dragon for a spell negate and two beefy bodies on board. Going second, Dingirsu -> Pain Gainer -> Zeus can be made for 1 non-targeting send and 2 fieldwipes as follow-up. 
  • Normal Summon: If you look closely at this deck, this deck only has 2 dedicated normal summons - 2 Aloof Lupines. That is because normal summons are typically saved for the Thunder Dragon monsters, since they all require only 1 tribute. Tributes for your summons are easy to obtain, since almost every monster special summons in this deck.  After you summon the Thunder Dragon monster, you can tribute it to special summon Colossus, given you used a thunder monster's effect in the hand that turn. 
  • Thunder Dragon Fusion in GY: In turn 3+, Thunder Dragon Fusion is your follow-up play. It normally searches Thunder Dragonroar so you can recycle Thunder Dragon Fusion to summon another Titan. It can also search Chaos Creator, which can further summon from the banished pile and trigger more banish effects from your GY!
  •  
Remember, the optimal endboard this deck can make going first is 3-4 negate Apollousa, a Titan with multiple pops, a Colossus to lock searching and a Hope Harbinger for a spell negate. That's usually enough to stop all your opponent's plays or have them instantly concede. 
 
Going second, this deck can easily make 8000+ attack on board and with multiple removals with Titan/Accesscode. While achieving gamestate, Chaos Thunderdragon should be able to shrug off most interruption - except floodgates. 
 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
GENERAL TIPS
  •  
  • Many of this deck's plays occur before committing to summoning a monster on board. Try to fish and bait for your opponent's interruptions before truly committing to your big plays.  
  •  
  • If you want to focus more on destroying multiple backrow, creating Thunder Dragon Titan is the ideal play, since it can pop cards on the field multiple times without targeting and can survive being destroyed multiple times (for ex. Torrential Tribute or Conquistador of the Golden Land).
  • Since this deck lacks an inherent normal summons and doesn’t really set cards, Denko Sekka can be decent budget option for the backrow decks you will face. She is also searchable off Thunder Dragon Fusion!
  •  
  • This deck is particularly weak to backrow, floodgates and high impact handtraps like Nibiru, Maxx "C", and Droll & Lockbird. 
  •  
  • Thunder Dragon Colossus is an extremely hard to kill instant-win button vs. common decks Flundereeze and heavily cripples decks like Branded Despia. If all your other plays have been stopped, at least try to get this purple menace out! 
  •  
  • Chaos Thunderdragon doesn't have an obvious "chokepoint" where a well-timed handtrap/interruption can end your turn. This deck slices through low-impact handtraps like nothing! 

CONCLUDING COMMENTARY

The synergy between Thunder Dragons, Chaos and Danger! almost seem like these three archetypes were designed to support each other! Thunder Dragons maintain hand advantage serving as discard fodder for Danger! cards as well as GY set-up for Chaos cards! Danger! allows free bodies on board with +1 draws while setting up the GY for Chaos cards we well! The synergies between these two are incredible!
 
Having enjoyed this deck's weaker incarnation in the TCG, witnessing it's unmitigated power complete with Colossus is a real treat! Colossus is a true powerhouse threat that shuts down many decks and avenues of play. A nice little bonus is the beautiful animation of this beauty everytime you summon Colossus and Titan - which is often the last thing your opponent will see before they surrender or get obliterated!

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: A non-meta accurate build of the man who screws the rules.
deck_description: This deck is based off the deck Kaiba used in the Dark Side of Dimensions movie and the recent support in Battles of Chaos. Let's not kid ourselves, this deck can and will brick. This deck uses updated cards in Kaiba's iconic strategies like Blue-Eyes and XYZ union. There are no synchros due to the deck being based off the DM era continuity. Cards in the side deck like Grinning Grave Virus and Loop of Destruction are examples of how I built this deck. Sunavalon Rikka, dos estrategia de plantas con un objetivos distintos, un deck que muchos les parece inofensivo pero no lo es. SUNAVALON Rikka estrategia ganadora del torneo que se celebró en Europa este año y sorprensivamente muchos se quedaron impactado que, que no ganó una estrategia dominante en el meta game, si no un deck de plantas. Sin duda nos queda en claro lo mucho a cambiado el juego desde que konami dividió dividirse en dos partes.

Sunavalon Rikka, two plant strategies with different objectives, a deck that seems harmless to many but is not. This strategy is very consistent, as both Rikka and Sunavalon received support in later sets. Without a doubt, it is clear to us how much the game has changed since Konami divided itself into two parts.

deck_excerpt: Budget Alternative to Thunder Danger Tearlaments
deck_description: This deck is pretty crazy for a budget build

Hi guys, welcome to my first Deck Guide! This is a fun casual deck i made from scratch by myself, so its probly not as optimal as it can be but its still fun as is.

The Deck is a fun and casual deck however it does have some anti meta shenanigans going for it. Going first without getting handtrapped againts a meta deck, you could set up a board to kill any graveyard effects and stop a dark ruler no more!. 

The deck is very cheap without the imperms, Infact im not a fan of the imperms as it slows the deck down alot. But i just put it here to fill the deck.

Deck Combo and starters:

1.) Magikey World: ALLWAYS DO THIS 1ST! This is a one card starter to get the magikeys going. If this resolves, search for Magikey Batobuster. Then use Magikey worlds 2nd effect to search for Magikey Maftea. You should have a normal monster in hand, hopefully, normal or special summon a normal monster to the field and then summon batobuster using Magikey Maftea. If you have a normal monster on the field, Magikey maftea allows you to use a normal monster from the deck as a material. ALWAYS TRY AND KEEP THE DOLLS EQUAL IN THE DECK eg: 2 madchens and 2 bear bears. On summon of batobuster you are allowed to search for ANY Magkiey card. We will search for Maginificent Magikey Mafteal and activate his effect to normal summon a magikey monster in addition to your normal summon. Doing this allows you to special summon a normal monster from the grave (the monster we used as a material) Your field should consist of 4 monsters now, make Magikey Fiend - Transfurlmine and Exosister Mikailis. Use mikailis to search for Exosister arment and Magikey Fiend - Transfurlmine to set a Magikey unlocking straight from the deck. With this,. your board consists of any exosister you need from the extra deck a spell/trap negate and a destroy on summon, all this off of magikey world!

2.) Doll Happiness : This is allways the last starter you use as it locks you into xyz (You cant use Magikey Fiend - Transfurlmine) On activation; search for grandpa dimedo or Box of friends. To set up a field, get box of friends. Doll happiness second effect is to destroy a card on the field or hand to send a doll from deck to grave. Destroy the box of friends and send a doll from deck to grave ( Keep the dolls equal in the deck!). Box of friends effect then activates to special summon 2 monsters with different names that either have 0 atk or def from the deck( If you used magikey world before using Doll happiness, make sure to use a different doll monster than the one you used for the batobuster material. THIS WILL KEEP THE DOLLS AT 2 in the deck. allowing more plays in the future). XYZ into the princess Cologne. This is already a lock by it self (read cologne and Doll happiness effects)

These are your 2 main starters and can be played with each other amongts other plays to set up a decently nasty field. 

Have fun playing the deck!

deck_name: Weather Painters. The best and most affordable anti-meta budget deck
deck_excerpt: Crushing the meta while also playing around relevant board breakers/hand traps
deck_description:
Starters:

Good opening hands include The Weather Painter Snow , or any weather painter monster plus The Weather Snowy Canvas / The Weather Forecast 

Another way to get to your combo is to have The Weather Painter Thunder  plus any of your continous spells. 

We also Include Small World  to get us to our other weather painters. The routes you can take depend on which handtraps you have availible to you.

Weather Painter/Canvas ratios and why they're correct:

We'll start with the common ratios. The Weather Forecast , The Weather Snowy Canvas , and The Weather Painter Snow at 3. As stated in the previous sections they're all starters to help you to get more cards, painter, and to get the link 3 The Weather Painter Rainbow 

The two weird ratios people may not agree with is three The Weather Painter Thunder , the two The Weather Painter Sun , and one The Weather Painter Cloud . The reason I think these are the ratios you should play is because The Weather Painter Thunder gets you to The Weather Snowy Canvas which gets you all of your other weather cards. You can also out your own Skill Drain , Anti-Spell Fragrance , or you can have him just to set off the effect of cloud. The Weather Painter Cloud is at one because by themselves they are basically a dead painter unless you already have the The Weather Forecast or The Weather Snowy Canvas . Two The Weather Painter Sun because using him as link material allows you to summon him back almost immidiently after which allows you to get more bodies on board quicker which is what weather painters struggle to do. 

Last but not least we have all the non-starter weather spell traps at 1 because most of the time we don't want to draw them. Instead we'll end up getting them by searching and/or placing the with The Weather Forecast or The Weather Painter Snow 

Anti-meta/Control:

Weather painters thrive in a control shell due to how they and their link monster interacts with the feild

First one is Anti-Spell Fragrance . Not only is this card a good anti-meta card that needs to see limits/bans, but also weather simply plays around this card without a problem. The Weather Forecast , The Weather Painter Snow , and The Weather Painter Thunder all activate from deck and therefore aren't effected by antispell. Anti-spell is also a great target for The Weather Painter Thunder to send for a weather spell/trap if you're in a pinch.

Second is Macro Cosmos which is very self explainatory. Most decks need a gy to function and Macro Cosmos takes that away from them. This is a instant win against decks like tearlaments and hinders spright so much to the point where it makes spright elf useless. It also works on decks that are also currently being run as anti meta like exosister. Having everything banished means they can't move their own cards out of their GY to xyz summon. Yet again another card that can be sent by The Weather Painter Thunder in a pinch.

Next is Solemn Judgment , A card that protects your backrow against things like Harpie's Feather Duster and others that are currently being run to out mystic mine. Speaking of this is also our mystic mine out that we use to negate the activation before they have a chance to use Beat Cop from the Underworld or Field Barrier . I've been switching between this and Solemn Strike but I weather painters deals with monsters much easier than spell/trap effects so most of the time Solemn Strike feels redundant.

The last two are my personal take on how to counter the meta but are also budget and there are better alternatives that I'll talk about later. These two are Drowning Mirror Force and Torrential Tribute . Torrential Tribute is by far the easier one to justify as Weather painters banish themselves as cost so they'll never get destroyed by torrential and you can also activate torrential inbetween painter summons to proc torrential and force out negates from your opponent. Next is Drowning Mirror Force which in all honesty I have a replacement I'll talk about in the next section that if you can afford you should absolutely do. However I think drowning is a amazing card against decks that produce monsters that cannot be destoryed or that have on death effects. Again a good example of a deck that hates this and doesn't run a out for is Tearlaments. They don't run spell trap negates and most of the time have limited back row removal. 

Replacements of budget options/Side deck options:

First off replace Drowning Mirror Force if you have access to three copies of Skill Drain . Weather painters banish themelves for cost so they dont losing anything from skill drain while skill drain also hurts every meta deck this format. Incase you planned on using the effect of one of your extra deck monsters you can send Skill Drain to the GY using The Weather Painter Thunder as his effect sends for cost.

Next Dimension Shifter is about to become budget with the upcoming crystal beast structure deck  and once it does you should absolutely mainboard it in the deck. Dimension Shifter also has 2200 def which allows it to be a small world target that can get you to The Weather Painter Snow especially if you decide to add more hand traps. 

Gamma is quite affordable at the moment and is currently one of the best handtraps in the format. It's also one of the few handtraps you can play under Dimension Shifter , Macro Cosmos , and Dimensional Fissure . I think this is a better alternative to infinite impermanence as it gives you more small world targets as well as being able to hit GY/Hand effects that Imperm can't deal with. 

Obviously Accesscode Talker instead of one of the topologic extra deck monsters works. You always end up getting your link fours out by using your backrow to make a link 3 weather monster then using one of your maindeck monsters as the foruth one. Same goes with making Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess with two negates. It's not ideal but in certain matchups and especially shuts down those random rouge decks before they make some crazy board. 

Red Reboot is a mandatory sideboard card. Weather can play through and if you want you can play Rivalry of Warlords but other floodgates like the There Can Be Only One or Gozen Match makes weather cry. 

Warning Point and Dimensional Barrier are key sideboard cards in my opinion and if you're feeling risky are worthy of a main board. Warning Point is going against the vast majority of decks but doesn't make it guaranteed to shut down your opponent. While Dimensional Barrier , a card that should be somewhere on the banlist, ftks certain decks. 

The fusion monsters in the extra deck are for Super Polymerization , a really good board breaker in the format however weather can't really use its own monsters for any of the fusions and doesn't get much off of discards so I highly reccomend to side board it instead of putting it in the main deck. However the card isn't exactly cheap so if you can affoard it then don't worry about you. You got yourself some extra deck space to play around with.

Last but not least if you're not worried about budget Pot of Prosperity is an amazing card for weather. Weather won't otk every time so the half damage doesn't matter and if you can get your specific peices of weather you can setup enough negates to stop your opponent. If you're a person who loves the thrill of gambling you can play Pot of Desires , however if you banish all 3 The Weather Forecast or all 3 The Weather Painter Snow or even all 3 The Weather Snowy Canvas you have basically lost. So I wouldn't reccomend but I've seen it be successful on occasion.

deck_name: Virtual World Ft. Baronne de Fleur

For Baronne de Fleur:

Normal Summon (Dark Bug) -> Special Summon a lvl 3 Tunner from the GY -> Synchro Summon (Cupid Pitch) -> Activate Cupid Pitch's effect and increase its level -> Synchro Summon (Baronne de Fleur) using a non-tuner lvl 3.

  • By Cupid Pitch's effect you can add a monster with 600 DEF from your deck to your hand (you have four options in this deck and you can also add P.U.N.K cards since all low level ones have exactly 600 DEF) and deal 1000 damage to your opponent.

- I always use Triple Tactics Talent, since in the actual meta game it's easy to use, so it's a free two card draw or steal an opponent's monster (in which case you should use it and don't let it return to your opponent's field at the end phase), however you can replace this card with another one that better suits your play style.

deck_excerpt: trying to make an odd-eyes deck
deck_description:
I have spent this month trying to make odd-eyes competitive, and with the current meta, this is the best I can do, this dragon monster mash of a deck has a lot of incidental synagy and recoverability. I am at heart a pendulum player.

odd-eyes revolution dragon as a great light target, the discard to search is not once per turn and helps set the graveyard

rokket dragon destruction effect triggers odd-eyes arc pendulum in scale to summon any odd-eyes monster from hand, deck and graveyard, this is great for extension, it can grab performapal odd-eyes synchron a level 2 tuner, performapal odd-eyes dissolver a monster polymerisation, or odd-eyes persona an effect veiler to extra deck monsters.

performapal odd-eyes synchron, in scale can turn every odd-eyes monster into a level 1 tuner, as a monster is can special summon one of your pendulum cards in scale and synchro immediately, giving access to baronne de fleur using odd-eyes dissolver, or odd-eyes meteor dragon using odd-eyes persona in scale. In a pinch aether and amophage sloth can be used to give you access to the magical dragon for more milling, or borreload savage to protect yourself while building a board.

Performapal odd-eyes dissolver give you access to fusion monster, odd-eyes vortex is an omni negate once per turn, but can also break board as when it is special summoned it can shuffle an face-up attack monster into players hand, trick monsters like mirrorjade won't get the boardwipe effect. When summon correctly odd-eyes arc pendulum, can summon odd-eyes vortex again on destruction from grave triggering it shuffle effect. Borreload furious seem look an odd pick in the build, however you may not have the pendulum monsters on board from odd-eyes vortex, furious dragon will still provide disruption and again the destruction of odd-eyes card trigger can summon persona from deck for a negate. 

supreme king dragon package, provide one the normal summon, giving you access to low scales to odd-eyes arc pendulum dragon high (8), the foolish burial and dragon shrine of darkwurm is a free summon and search. Dragon shrine can also foolish an odd-eyes arc pendulum as an extra, thinning the deck and setting up graveyard with dark. Gate zero is actually not your best low scale, that go to odd-eyes persona, it actually the monster effect, destroying itself and odd-eyes card trigger odd-eyes arc pendulum, while summoning a fusion, or syncho dragon, your targets are furious dragon and dragonshell, bare in mind there effect are negated and they have 0 atk/def, what we are after in the graveyard effect, furious dragon allows you to special summon borrelend from grave if your opponent managed to out it, and dragonshell while it can be synchro summoned to recycle borreload savage, magical dragon and baronne, it can equip itself to a monster summoned from the extra deck, on attack declaration allow you to draw a card.

aether and amorphage sloth are your seal targets, aether can banish a monster on special summon, goes to the extra deck and can be pendulum summoned again. Sloth is the side deck alternative, it is big enough to attack over winda when pendulum summoned, but when you have been dark rulered, your can still trigger seal, as it tribute is cost summon sloth preventing your opponent from FTK.

the rest of the deck is just the dragon-link core goodness.

the pendulum best synagy is with rokket tracer and boot sector launch. boot on field is broken for follow up plays, and there is just so much value keeping it on field, and there are times when i used seal to return boot to hand so i could have the followup play. The pendulum monster in scale are great being you face card target for rokket tracer to extend with.

less optimium play result in seal pass, pendulum heavy hand seal pass with vortex, most of your play will end on borrelend and hot red, but the followup in graveyard and extra deck 

the hand trap is as you like for your locals, as is you side deck i choose veiler over infinite because it a light target. The cosmic are for anti-spell fragrance, and mystic mine can be dealt with by spiral flame strike, a non once per turn rota and pop when an odd-eyes card is on the field, whether as a monster or in scales.

This month has been difficult with this architype, as pendulum is just not in the best place, but in term of dragon-link it does rise the floor and ceiling by involving another summoning mechanic. 

So please have fun and tell me would you think.

This deck aims to use the current and new tools that Adventure Spright can offer!

This deck is using the Nimble engine, this is very specific because the newly aquired Spright Sprind enables Nimble Angler which puts 2 level 2 bodies on board. The nimble engine also helps Spright's grind game as Nimble Beaver also summons from grave. Not only this, Nimble Angler also helps against Ishizu Tear with how much they mill, it gets Spright bodies on board before their turn even starts, forcing the Ishizu Tear player to spend resources to destroy them otherwise you will pop off

I am using the Adventurer engine as it not only is a strong negate which Spright loves to have but can also act as Swap Frog fodder from hand (if you have Enchantress in hand) and this deck doesn't need its normal so Rite of Aramesir's restriction is mostly negligable.

In the side deck is a Cyber-Stein and Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon. Spright Sprind can send the Stein from deck to grave and Spright Elf can summon it back so you can summon your Dragoon without running a brick (except Stein itself). Dragoon does NOT gain its destruction effect, only the negation effect but i think its more than enough. Other options you can run include DPE, Exterio, Last Warrior From Another Planet and any others you want to try

deck_excerpt: Take 2 on Krawler Tindangle! I'm coming around on the combination!
deck_description:
This is a second take on a Krawler Tindangle list. My first build can be found here, and as you can see I was less than hopeful on the archetypes' potential synergies. I've revisited the deck, however, and I think I've found a build that's a lot more synergistic and consistent! I've trimmed the list to 42 cards and removed the draw cards. They help the deck's consistency an incredible amount, but we need to keep as many of our names in rotation as possible (either for Soma's summons, or making Acute Cerberus). The current build of this deck aims to flood the field with flip-monsters that float into other bodies so that on our following turn we can link off into game winners like Unchained Abomination and Accesscode Talker.

 

This deck is meant to highlight Tindangles, so we are including enough bodies and cards to reliably make Acute Cerberus. We are on 2 Base Gardna to increase our chances of milling it, as we need it to make Acute Cerb. The Dholes and Deluanay are also at 2 to increase the mill odds, and we can discard all of these cards with Barricadeborg Blocker if need be. We play Survivor at 3 to give us a good mill engine, and Jhrelth at 3 to send from hand and deck. Small world is crucial for finding our combo pieces, and our main bridges are Guard Dog, who can be used to shut down the opponent for a turn, and Chronomaly Colossal Head, who can flip the opponent's monsters or our own. The Krawler engine is 3 Soma, 2 Dendrite, and 1 Glial, with 3 Girsu to support them. We send Mind Meld to GY off of Girsu, then set Pawns after making Lib. Nibiru is our main source of disruption for the opponent, and Lord of the Heavenly Prison to protect our face-downs. Since we are on 3 Survivor, we are playing a Link-heavy extra deck. We use it to toolbox our way out of difficult scenarios and push for game once we've build a strong enough board.

 

I won't re-tread the combos and Small World bridges in this decklist, but I want to emphasize that this deck wants to win on turn 3-4. Our main goal is to live long enough to take advantage of our recursive summoning and floating bodies. This deck doesn't break boards very well, and doesn't make unbreakable boards, but if we go first we can set up Winda, and if we go second we can use Sol and Luna to help us set and activate our flip-monsters. If you would like a more detailed deck description or lines of play, please leave a comment down below! I'm happy to provide more info on any aspects of the deck, and am open to suggestions for this or other decks! Thanks for reading, and I hope your day goes well!

deck_excerpt: Extra decks are garbage in this deck, literally. Throw out your Extra Deck so your opponent will literally throw out theirs!
deck_description:
Deck Details and Tips

 

The key focus of this deck is utilizing your extra deck as tribute fodder for ritual summons. To this end, Shaddols are utilized as an optional lock play, while the Fossils, and Elder Entity are to be used explictly as secondary removal. The Herald and Albaz cards are secondary card advantage for you to further your plays, but are to be viewed as secondary options to the control choices. The level 9 and 10 cards are solely present to be used to multisummon your nekroz ritual monsters, but they are otherwise wholly unimportant to the deck. If you are forced to remove cards from your extra deck by an opponent's effect, these should be the first choice. 

The Impcantation engine is present solely as a back up search options in the case where you did not draw any of the nekroz pieces. They are not important to your deck's function and should be viewed as wholly disposable in cases where your engine is online. 

The dogmatika ritual monsters are your closer of choice in most games, while also being decent disruption against extra deck combo decks (Fallen of Albaz, Despia, Syncron, etc.). The non ritual engine is a powerful control secondary option in cases where you can not ritual summon, or your running out of steam in a longer game. Use the non ritual cards present to stifle opponent's plays while moving to close out the game. 

The most important part of the deck, the Nekroz are present largely to enable you to play Nekroz of Unicore, which is fundamentally a core wincon to your list. If you have Unicore out turn 1, your should have little to no problem outplaying and outvaluing most decks. Brionac is your secondary choice, especially in a go-second state, as he will be very effecient in removal and in baiting out your opponent's negate options. 

Lastly, the finishing touch of the deck is the Shaddol Schism. First and foremost, this is always a garnet if it is drawn first turn. This card is best when searched using Shaddol Apkallone as a ritual material, as it will enable you to fusion summon into Shaddol Winda during the opponents turn, giving you a powerful board into their turn. 

----


Weaknesses

 

This deck suffers to Kaijus, it can not really outplay it, as the endboard will often be 1-2 creatures that act as floodgates. 
It lacks any real way to deal with Floowanderize, and will be completely stifled against them. The same can be said for Monarch decks.

Due to the removal being largely creature based, skill drain is a very serious issue for this deck to play around, it is possible but not something you can reasonably deal with on the board. 

Due to not having any form of Link summoning in this list, some more obscure forms of control, Iblee for example, will be incredible hard to deal with.

Lastly, Helios type effects that banish the gy will restrict your options for extending plays, but should be reasonably playable regardless. 

-----

Strengths

 

When going first you can easily cripple Despia decks.

Synchro decks that rely on key cards in the extra deck will be heavily limited in their options. 

The information you can have over the opponent will give you significant advantage in choosing your follow ups. 

Link Climbing decks will be heavily limited in their ability to build an end board. 

It is very effective at rebuilding boards after being removed, and has access to a multitude of gy effects that will give you advantage against heavy removal based control decks. 

This deck is heavily augmentable to fit floodgates, as there are 3 engines present, you can easily change ratios to add in There Can Only Be One, Gozen Match, Summon Limit, or And The Band Played On, depending on your needs.
